1 Revisiting Lab 2

Reading In The Packages and Data Set

Code 
library(tidyverse)
library(lubridate)
surveys <- read_csv(here::here("Labs", "Lab 2", "surveys.csv"))

1. Reorder the species so the boxplots for weights go in descending order (largest to smallest).

Code 
ggplot(data = surveys,
  mapping = aes(x = weight, 
                y = fct_reorder(species, weight))) + 
  geom_jitter(color = "darkseagreen", 
              size = 0.5, 
              alpha = 0.5) + 
  geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.1, 
               outlier.shape = NA)

2. Now that you've reordered, look at your y-axis label. That's long! Let's take Will Chase's advice and move the y-axis label to the top of the plot.

Code 
# removing axis labels: https://www.datanovia.com/en/blog/ggplot-axis-labels/

ggplot(data = surveys,
  mapping = aes(x = weight, 
                y = fct_reorder(species, weight))) + 
  geom_jitter(color = "darkseagreen", 
              size = 0.5, 
              alpha = 0.5) + 
  geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.1, 
               outlier.shape = NA) + 
  labs(x = "Weight (g)",
       title = "Weight Distribution Within Different Rodent Species") +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(axis.title.y = element_blank(), 
        plot.title = element_text(face = "bold",
                                  size = 15))

2 Time Series Plot

1. Create a visualization how weights vary for each genus over the duration of the study.

Code 
surveys2 <- surveys |> select(year, genus, weight)

# there seems to be overplotting of points
ggplot(data = surveys2, mapping = aes(x = year, y = weight, color = genus)) + 
  geom_line()
Code 
# there is still overplotting
ggplot(data = surveys2, mapping = aes(x = year, y = weight)) + 
  geom_line() + facet_wrap(~ genus)

2. Â Calculate and plot the mean weight for each genus for each year.

Code 
timeSummary <- surveys |> 
  select(year, genus, weight) |> 
  group_by(year, genus) |>
  summarise(meanWeight = mean(weight))

ggplot(data = timeSummary, 
       mapping = aes(x = year,
                     y = meanWeight, 
                     color = genus)) + 
  geom_line()

3. Reorder the lines so the mean weights go in descending order (largest to smallest).

4. Now that you've reordered the lines, look at your legend's label. That's terrible! Let's give the legend a new titleÂ andÂ move the information from the y-axis to the plot title.

Code 
ggplot(data = timeSummary, 
       mapping = aes(x = year,
                     y = meanWeight,
                     color = fct_reorder(genus, meanWeight, .desc = TRUE))) + 
  geom_line() + 
  labs(x = "Years",
       title = "Mean Weight (g) of Different Rodent Genuses From 1979 - 2002", 
       color = "Rodent Genus") + 
  theme_light() + 
  theme(axis.title.y = element_blank(),
        plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 7))

3 Captures Over the Week

1. Create a visualization of the number of rodents captured each day of the week.

Code 
captures <- surveys |> filter(!is.na(day_of_week))

ggplot(data = captures, mapping = aes(x = day_of_week)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "count")

2. Change the order of the day of the week to go Monday through Sunday.

Code 
weekDays <- c("Mon", "Tue", "Wed", "Thu", "Fri", "Sat", "Sun")

ggplot(data = captures, mapping = aes(x = factor(day_of_week, weekDays))) +
  geom_bar(stat = "count", fill = "lightseagreen") + 
  labs(x = "Days of The Week",
       title = "Total Number of Rodents Captured Across the Days of The Week") +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(axis.title.y = element_blank(),
        plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 8))

3. Collapse Monday through Friday into a "Weekday" level, and collapse Saturday and Sunday into a "Weekend"Â level. Plot the number of rodents captured between the two groups.

Code 
# removing a legend: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/35618260/remove-legend-ggplot-2-2

weekDays <- c("Mon", "Tue", "Wed", "Thu", "Fri")
weekEnd <- c("Sat", "Sun")

collapsedDay <- surveys |> 
  mutate(day = fct_collapse(day_of_week, "Weekday" = weekDays, "Weekend" = weekEnd)) |> 
  filter(!is.na(day))
          
ggplot(data = collapsedDay, mapping = aes(x = day, fill = day)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "count", width = 0.4) + 
  labs(title = "Total Number of Rodents Captured: Weekdays vs. Weekends") +
  theme_linedraw() +
  theme(axis.title.y = element_blank(), 
        axis.title.x = element_blank(),
        legend.position = "none",
        plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"))

## 1 Revisiting Lab 2

### Reading In The Packages and Data Set

```{r}
library(tidyverse)
library(lubridate)
surveys <- read_csv(here::here("Labs", "Lab 2", "surveys.csv"))
```

**1. Reorder the species so the boxplots for weights go in descending order (largest to smallest).**

```{r boxplot-jitter-points, fig.align = 'center'}

ggplot(data = surveys,
  mapping = aes(x = weight, 
                y = fct_reorder(species, weight))) + 
  geom_jitter(color = "darkseagreen", 
              size = 0.5, 
              alpha = 0.5) + 
  geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.1, 
               outlier.shape = NA) 
```

**2. Now that you\'ve reordered, look at your y-axis label. That\'s long! Let\'s take Will Chase\'s advice and move the y-axis label to the top of the plot.**

```{r, fig.align = 'center'}
# removing axis labels: https://www.datanovia.com/en/blog/ggplot-axis-labels/

ggplot(data = surveys,
  mapping = aes(x = weight, 
                y = fct_reorder(species, weight))) + 
  geom_jitter(color = "darkseagreen", 
              size = 0.5, 
              alpha = 0.5) + 
  geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.1, 
               outlier.shape = NA) +
```

## 2 Time Series Plot

**1. Create a visualization how weights vary for each genus over the duration of the study.**

```{r, fig.align = 'center'}
surveys2 <- surveys |> select(year, genus, weight)

# there seems to be overplotting of points
ggplot(data = surveys2, mapping = aes(x = year, y = weight, color = genus)) + 
  geom_line()

# there is still overplotting
ggplot(data = surveys2, mapping = aes(x = year, y = weight)) + 
  geom_line() + facet_wrap(~ genus)
```

**2. Â Calculate and plot the mean weight for each genus for each year.**

```{r, fig.align = 'center'}

timeSummary <- surveys |> 
  select(year, genus, weight) |> 
  group_by(year, genus) |>
  summarise(meanWeight = mean(weight))

ggplot(data = timeSummary, 
       mapping = aes(x = year,
                     y = meanWeight, 
                     color = genus)) + 
  geom_line() 
```

**3. Reorder the lines so the mean weights go in descending order (largest to smallest).**

**4. Now that you\'ve reordered the lines, look at your legend\'s label. That\'s terrible! Let\'s give the legend a new titleÂ *and*Â move the information from the y-axis to the plot title.**

```{r, fig.align = 'center'}
  
ggplot(data = timeSummary, 
       mapping = aes(x = year,
                     y = meanWeight,
                     color = fct_reorder(genus, meanWeight, .desc = TRUE))) + 
  geom_line() + 
  labs(x = "Years",
       title = "Mean Weight (g) of Different Rodent Genuses From 1979 - 2002", 
       color = "Rodent Genus") + 
  theme_light() + 
  theme(axis.title.y = element_blank(),
        plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 7)) 
```

## **3 Captures Over the Week**

**1. Create a visualization of the number of rodents captured each day of the week.**

```{r, fig.align = 'center'}
captures <- surveys |> filter(!is.na(day_of_week))

ggplot(data = captures, mapping = aes(x = day_of_week)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "count")
```

**2. Change the order of the day of the week to go Monday through Sunday.**

```{r, fig.align = 'center'}
weekDays <- c("Mon", "Tue", "Wed", "Thu", "Fri", "Sat", "Sun")

ggplot(data = captures, mapping = aes(x = factor(day_of_week, weekDays))) +
  geom_bar(stat = "count", fill = "lightseagreen") + 
  labs(x = "Days of The Week",
       title = "Total Number of Rodents Captured Across the Days of The Week") +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(axis.title.y = element_blank(),
        plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 8)) 
```

**3. Collapse Monday through Friday into a `"Weekday"` level, and collapse Saturday and Sunday into a `"Weekend"`Â level. Plot the number of rodents captured between the two groups.**

```{r, fig.align = 'center'}
# removing a legend: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/35618260/remove-legend-ggplot-2-2

weekDays <- c("Mon", "Tue", "Wed", "Thu", "Fri")
weekEnd <- c("Sat", "Sun")

collapsedDay <- surveys |> 
  mutate(day = fct_collapse(day_of_week, "Weekday" = weekDays, "Weekend" = weekEnd)) |> 
  filter(!is.na(day))
          
ggplot(data = collapsedDay, mapping = aes(x = day, fill = day)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "count", width = 0.4) + 
  labs(title = "Total Number of Rodents Captured: Weekdays vs. Weekends") +
  theme_linedraw() +
  theme(axis.title.y = element_blank(), 
        axis.title.x = element_blank(),
        legend.position = "none",
        plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"))
```
